# Cron Architecture (audric side, post-v0.7d Block C)

> ✅ **Migration complete (v0.7d Phase 6, 2026-05-21):** every t2000 ECS cron has been retired (Block A — S.221, Block B — S.222, Block C — S.224). Audric now owns its own scheduled work via Vercel native cron. The t2000 `apps/server` package + `infra/` Fargate stack were deleted in S.224 (t2000 commit `5e04154f`).

Audric's scheduled work lives in **two places**:

1. **`/api/cron/*` routes** — Vercel native cron entrypoints. Schedule defined in `apps/web/vercel.json`. Authenticated by `Authorization: Bearer ${CRON_SECRET}` (Vercel injects this automatically when the env var is set).
2. **`/api/internal/payments`** — the SOLE surviving internal route. Engine payment-link / invoice tools call it server-side via `x-internal-key: ${T2000_INTERNAL_KEY}` dual-auth.

## The endpoints (post-Block-C reality)

| Route | Writes | Triggered by |
|---|---|---|
| `GET /api/cron/portfolio-snapshot` | `PortfolioSnapshot` | Vercel cron — daily 07:00 UTC |
| `POST /api/cron/financial-context-snapshot` | `UserFinancialContext` | Vercel cron — daily 02:30 UTC |
| `POST /api/internal/payments` | `Payment` (CRUD for payment-link / invoice tools) | Engine server-side fetch |

> **Deleted in v0.7d Phase 6 (S.221, S.222, S.224 — 2026-05-21):**
> - `POST /api/internal/memory-extraction` (Claude-driven UserMemory writes — S.221)
> - `POST /api/internal/profile-inference` (Claude-driven UserFinancialProfile writes — S.221)
> - `POST /api/internal/chain-memory` (7-classifier ChainFact writes — S.221)
> - `POST /api/cron/user-memory-retention` (UserMemory retention sweep — S.221)
> - `POST /api/internal/portfolio-snapshot` (ECS receiver — S.224; Vercel cron at `/api/cron/portfolio-snapshot` is the replacement)
> - `POST /api/internal/financial-context-snapshot` (ECS receiver — S.224; Vercel cron at `/api/cron/financial-context-snapshot` is the replacement)
> - `GET /api/internal/health-factor` (ECS HF-alert cron — retired S.31 April 2026, route deleted S.224)
> - `POST /api/internal/notification-users` (ECS cron user-list join — S.224; Vercel cron jobs read `prisma.user.findMany` directly)
> - `GET /api/internal/user-address` (ECS cron user-lookup — S.224)
> - `POST /api/internal/app-event` (ECS cron event sink — S.224)
>
> Memory writes replaced by MemWal SDK (web-v2 `Experimental_Agent` + `prepareStep` recall + `onFinish` `memwal.analyze()` write).

## Auth — two distinct gates

### Vercel cron routes (`/api/cron/*`)

Validate `Authorization: Bearer ${CRON_SECRET}` first line:

```typescript
import { env } from '@/lib/env';

export async function GET(req: NextRequest): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const auth = req.headers.get('authorization');
  if (auth !== `Bearer ${env.CRON_SECRET}`) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }, { status: 401 });
  }
  const result = await runPortfolioSnapshotJob();
  return NextResponse.json(result);
}
```

`CRON_SECRET` is required env (boot fails if missing). Vercel auto-injects the `Authorization: Bearer` header on scheduled invocations; manual triggers must supply it explicitly.

### `/api/internal/payments` route (engine bridge)

Validate `x-internal-key: ${T2000_INTERNAL_KEY}` via the shared helper:

```typescript
import { validateInternalKey } from '@/lib/internal-auth';

export async function POST(req: NextRequest): Promise<NextResponse> {
  const auth = validateInternalKey(req.headers.get('x-internal-key'));
  if ('error' in auth) return auth.error;
  // ... do the work
}
```

**Never** assume "internal" means "no auth needed." Vercel functions are public HTTPS endpoints; the auth gate is the only security boundary.

> **Why `T2000_INTERNAL_KEY` still exists after Block C:** the engine runs server-side (inside the audric Next.js process for `apps/web`, alongside `apps/web-v2` chat) and calls audric APIs via HTTP self-fetches. It cannot present a zkLogin JWT (server context has no browser session), so the dual-auth path in `authenticateAnalyticsRequest()` accepts `x-internal-key` as the trusted-server alternative. Slated for full elimination in v0.7e+ via the function-injection refactor — see `HANDOFF_NEXT_AGENT.md` backlog row `engine-fn-injection-refactor`.

## Idempotency — every cron job MUST be safe to re-run

Vercel cron WILL retry on failure / timeout. Use upserts, not creates:

```typescript
// ✅ Idempotent
await prisma.portfolioSnapshot.upsert({
  where: { userId_date: { userId, date: today } },
  create: { userId, date: today, ...metrics },
  update: { ...metrics },
});

// ❌ Not idempotent — second call creates duplicate row
await prisma.portfolioSnapshot.create({ data: { userId, date: today, ...metrics } });
```

For the current Vercel crons:
- `portfolio-snapshot`: skips users with an existing row for today (idempotent by `userId_date`).
- `financial-context-snapshot`: `upsert` keyed on `userId` (idempotent).

## Job implementation — extract to `lib/jobs/*`

The route file is thin. Real work lives in `apps/web/lib/jobs/<name>.ts`. This pattern was set in Block B to share impls between legacy ECS-cron-receiver and new Vercel-cron paths; the receivers are gone, but the separation still helps:
- Routes own auth + response shape.
- Jobs own the work + are testable in isolation.

```typescript
// apps/web/lib/jobs/portfolio-snapshot.ts
export async function runPortfolioSnapshotJob(): Promise<PortfolioSnapshotResult> {
  // ... fetch users, snapshot each, return aggregate counts
}

// apps/web/app/api/cron/portfolio-snapshot/route.ts
export async function GET(req: NextRequest) {
  // auth check
  const result = await runPortfolioSnapshotJob();
  return NextResponse.json(result);
}
```

## Scale notes

- **Current scale:** single-shard runs comfortably fit Vercel's 300s `maxDuration` cap.
- **When sharding becomes necessary:** if active users grow past ~200 (where 200 × 1.5s = 300s starts to bite for fin-ctx-snapshot), the route can fan out via internal `fetch()` to itself with `{ shard, total }` params. `runFinancialContextSnapshotJob()` already accepts these; route just needs the fan-out logic.
- **No EventBridge / no ECS:** zero AWS scheduler involvement post-Block-C. `vercel.json` is the single source of truth for cron schedules.

## Response shape — uniform across cron routes

```typescript
return NextResponse.json({
  created: 100,
  skipped: 50,
  errors: 2,
  total: 152,
});
```

Vercel Logs UI surfaces these counts; deviation from this shape breaks cron observability.

## What MUST NOT happen

```typescript
// ❌ Cron route that hits Sui RPC per user (10k calls = rate limit)
for (const user of users) {
  await suiClient.getAllBalances({ owner: user.suiAddress });
}
// — go through the canonical getPortfolio (it caches via the 60s in-process cache).

// ❌ Cron route that writes to multiple domains
// — financial-context shouldn't also update UserMemory. One job, one domain.

// ❌ Cron route that responds with HTML / a redirect
return NextResponse.redirect('/some-page');
// — cron routes are JSON-only.

// ❌ Skipping the auth check (CRON_SECRET or x-internal-key)
// — lib/internal-auth.ts + the bearer-check pattern are one-liners; use them.

// ❌ Reintroducing an /api/internal/* receiver route for a "remote caller"
// — there is no remote caller anymore (t2000 ECS retired). New scheduled work
//   becomes a /api/cron/* Vercel route + a vercel.json entry. New
//   engine-bridge routes that absolutely cannot be done via function injection
//   need an explicit lock from the rule file owner.
```

## Adding a new cron job

1. Create `apps/web/lib/jobs/<job>.ts` with the work + a `run...Job()` export returning `{ created, skipped, errors, total }`.
2. Create `apps/web/app/api/cron/<job>/route.ts` — bearer auth first line, call the job impl, return JSON.
3. Add the schedule to `apps/web/vercel.json` (`vercel project inspect` confirms Root Directory = `apps/web`; `vercel crons list` is the ground truth).
4. Make the job idempotent (upsert).
5. Verify locally: `curl -H "Authorization: Bearer $CRON_SECRET" https://<deploy>/api/cron/<job>` returns the expected counts.
6. Update `prisma-models-overview.mdc` if it writes to a model not yet listed there.

